Conceptually, the X.500 directory service is extremely general, and is
capable of handling names for anything out in the network.  Also
conceptually, a single implementation of the directory could handle a
wide variety of objects.  However, it is not clear to me that a
one-size-fits-all approach to implementation (or even standardization)
is always best.  There is a broad range of problems to which a
directory service might be applied.  The performance and other
characteristics of a monolithic, undiversified directory service might
fit some applications well but other applications poorly.

I agree with your observation that all technical problems have not yet
been solved.  Reading through X.500 reveals a host of unanswered
questions and unresolved issues, some of them very thorny.  The good
people of CCITT and ISO have another study period's worth of work in
front of them.

--Debbie

